# 1️⃣ URL (Uniform Resource Locator)

A URL is the address of a resource available on the Internet.

### Example

```
https://www.google.com
```

The browser uses this address to determine which website you want to access.

---

# 2️⃣ Browser

A browser is a software application used to access websites.

Popular browsers include:

- Google Chrome
- Mozilla Firefox
- Microsoft Edge
- Brave
- Safari

The browser is considered the **client** because it requests resources from a web server.

---

# 3️⃣ DNS Lookup

Humans prefer remembering names such as:

```
google.com
```

Computers communicate using IP addresses.

```
142.250.xxx.xxx
```

The **Domain Name System (DNS)** converts domain names into IP addresses.

### Example

```
google.com

↓

142.250.xxx.xxx
```

### Real-World Analogy

DNS works like the contact list on your phone.

You remember:

```
Mom
```

Your phone remembers:

```
+91xxxxxxxxxx
```

---

# 4️⃣ TCP Connection

Once the browser knows the server's IP address, it establishes a TCP connection.

This begins with the **Three-Way Handshake**.

```
SYN

↓

SYN-ACK

↓

ACK
```

Only after this handshake can reliable communication begin.

---

# 5️⃣ HTTPS and TLS

Modern websites use HTTPS instead of HTTP.

HTTPS protects communication by encrypting data using TLS (Transport Layer Security).

Encryption protects sensitive information such as:

- Passwords
- Credit card numbers
- Cookies
- Personal information

Without HTTPS, attackers could potentially read or modify the transmitted data.

---

# 6️⃣ HTTP Request

After the secure connection is established, the browser sends an HTTP request to the web server.

Example:

```http
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: google.com
User-Agent: Chrome
Accept: text/html
```

Think of this request as politely asking:

> "Please send me your homepage."

---

# 7️⃣ Server Processing

The server receives the request and processes it.

Depending on the request, it may:

- Retrieve files
- Query a database
- Verify authentication
- Check permissions
- Execute server-side code

Finally, it prepares a response.

---

# 8️⃣ HTTP Response

The server replies with an HTTP response.

Example:

```http
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/html

<html>
...
</html>
```

The response usually contains:

- Status Code
- Headers
- HTML Content
- CSS
- JavaScript
- Images

---

# 9️⃣ Browser Rendering

After receiving the response, the browser starts rendering the webpage.

The browser reads:

- HTML
- CSS
- JavaScript
- Fonts
- Images

It then combines all these resources and displays the final webpage.

